  "bib_entries": {
    "6156701": {
      "title": "Preconditioning with ischemia: A delay of lethal cell injury in ischemic myocardium",
      "abstract": "We have previously shown that a brief episode of ischemia slows the rate of ATP depletion during subsequent ischemic episodes. Additionally, intermittent reperfusion may be beneficial to the myocardium by washing out catabolites that have accumulated during ischemia. Thus, we proposed that multiple brief ischemic episodes might actually protect the heart from a subsequent sustained ischemic insult. To test this hypothesis, two sets of experiments were performed. In the first set, one group of dogs (n = 7) was preconditioned with four 5 min circumflex occlusions, each separated by 5 min of reperfusion, followed by a sustained 40 min occlusion. The control group (n = 5) received a single 40 min occlusion. In the second study, an identical preconditioning protocol was followed, and animals (n = 9) then received a sustained 3 hr occlusion. Control animals (n = 7) received a single 3 hr occlusion. Animals were allowed 4 days of reperfusion thereafter. Histologic infarct size then was measured and was related t..."
    },
    "91192018": {
      "title": "The role of adenosine in ischemic preconditioning",
      "abstract": "Exposing the heart to only 5 min of regional ischemia followed by reperfusion renders it very resistant to infarction from a subsequent ischemic insult. This change represents a biochemical change in the tissue which we believe is triggered by adenosine A1 type receptors. The protection lasts for less than an hour and additional periods of ischemia offer no additional protection. Recent studies in rabbit hearts suggest that adenosine receptors are coupled to phospholipase C via a pertussis toxin-sensitive G protein. Phospholipase C activity activates protein kinase C which protects by phosphorylating a protective protein early in the ischemic period. We believe that preconditioning acts to up-regulate protein kinase C, perhaps by translocating it into the sarcolemma. Any receptor in the myocyte coupled to phospholipase C should be capable of putting the heart into the preconditioned state. That has been verified for the alpha-1 and the muscarinic M2 receptors. Because pharmacologic preconditioning must precede ischemia we have been examining whether adenosine-induced protection can be maintained indefinitely. Unfortunately, after only 3 days of treatment tolerance develops to A1-selective agonists with a loss of protection as well the ability to protect with ischemic preconditioning."
    }
  },
